      • nextPass

        public double nextPass
        Julian day of the next pass of the satellite above observer, local time. If negative that means that the satellite is eclipsed during the next pass. If zero then the event could not be calculated.

      • iridiumAngle

        public float iridiumAngle
        The smallest iridium angle in degrees. A given Iridium satellite will be flaring if it is not eclipsed, above the horizon, and this value is lower than 2. An empirical relationship between this angle and the brightness of the reflection has been determined (Randy John, 2002, SKYSAT v0.64, see http://home.comcast.net/~skysat). 2 deg corresponds to about 0 mag, 0.5° to -3 mag. The brightest flares are -8 or -9 mag (visible during day), and can last from 10 to 30s.

        Constructs a satellite ephem object giving all the data.
        Parameters:
        nom - Name of the satellite.
        ra - Right ascension.
        dec - Declination.
        dist - Distance.
        azi - Azimuth.
        ele - Elevation
        selon - Sub-Earth longitude.
        selat - Sub-Earth latitude.
        sedist - Sub-Earth distance above sea level.
        speed - Topocentric relative speed.
        elo - Elongation.
        ill - Illumination fraction.
        st - True if the satellite if eclipsed, false otherwise.
        rev - Number of revolutions completed.
